          "body": "The northern kingdom's five kings in this chapter represent the complete collapse of dynastic legitimacy. Zechariah (six months), Shallum (one month), Menahem (ten years), Pekahiah (two years), and Pekah (twenty years) — only Menahem dies in his bed and bequeaths his throne to his son (15:22). The rest are assassinated by conspirators who themselves become targets. The word for 'conspired' (qashar, 15:10, 25, 30) is the political vocabulary of treachery, and its triple appearance signals that conspiracy has become the de facto constitution of the northern kingdom. The Deuteronomistic historian does not argue this point; he records it and lets the reader draw the conclusion: when a nation will not be governed by God's word, it will be governed by the sword."
