          "title": "Menahem and Assyria — tribute as symptom",
          "body": "The Assyrian episode of verses 19-20 is brief but theologically loaded. Tiglath-pileser III (called 'Pul,' his Babylonian throne-name) comes against the land, and Menahem does not fight or pray — he pays. One thousand talents of silver, extracted by taxing Israel's wealthy class fifty shekels each, buys the king's departure. The narrator notes Menahem's motive: 'that his hand might be with him to strengthen the kingdom under his rule' (15:19). He is not seeking Yahweh to strengthen his kingdom; he is seeking Assyria. This is the logic the prophets name as harlotry (Hosea 8:9 calls it explicitly: 'Ephraim has hired lovers among the nations'). The irony is complete: a king who would not submit to Yahweh's covenant submits to a pagan superpower's tribute demands. The tribute buys a decade; the deportation comes under the next king."
