          "title": "The first deportation — 15:29 and the map of judgment",
          "body": "Verse 29 is the chapter's most consequential verse and one of the most significant in the entire book. Tiglath-pileser III — now named by his Assyrian throne-name rather than his Babylonian one — captures a sweeping geography: Ijon, Abel-beth-maacah, Janoah, Kedesh, Hazor, Gilead, Galilee, and 'all the land of Naphtali.' These are the northern and Transjordanian territories — the land of Zebulun and Naphtali, the Galilee of the nations. The verb 'carried them captive' (galah, 15:29) is the exile-word; this is the first deportation of Israelites into Assyrian captivity, a full decade before Samaria itself falls (2 Kings 17:6). The student of Isaiah 9:1 will recognize these exact territories as the ones promised to see 'a great light' — Matthew 4:12-17 quotes Isaiah 9:1-2 to frame Jesus's Galilean ministry as the redemptive reversal of 2 Kings 15:29. The geography of judgment is already the geography of hope."
